"Chauvin F., Royer J.-F., Déqué M.","Response of hurricane-type vortices to global warming as simulated by ARPEGE-Climat at high resolution",2006,"Climate Dynamics","27","4",,"377","399",,,10.1007/s00382-006-0135-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33745712485&partnerID=40&md5=208a5c3c47373e5efe40899ffb2980d0","Météo-France/CNRM, 42 Avenue Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France; CNRM/GMGEC/UDC, Météo-France, 42 Avenue G. Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse Cedex 01, France","Chauvin, F., Météo-France/CNRM, 42 Avenue Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France, CNRM/GMGEC/UDC, Météo-France, 42 Avenue G. Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse Cedex 01, France; Royer, J.-F., Météo-France/CNRM, 42 Avenue Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France; Déqué, M., Météo-France/CNRM, 42 Avenue Coriolis, 31057 Toulouse, France","Atlantic hurricanes and their sensitivity to anthropogenic warming are investigated using very high (0.5°×0.5° over the Atlantic domain) resolution global simulations. The ARPEGE-Climat variable resolution grid demonstrates its usefulness in regional climate studies since resolution can be multiplied by a factor of 2.5 over the domain of interest compared to a uniform grid, for a similar computer cost. The question of hurricane characteristics dependence on anthropogenic warming is tackled trough the implementation of a tracking method. Changes in the total number, as well as locations, of hurricanes appear to depend more on sea surface temperature (SST) spatial patterns anomaly than Atlantic mean intensity, essentially through the change in large scale vertical wind shear. A uniform SST anomaly forcing produces increased and eastward shifted systems while a spatially contrasted anomaly leads to a decrease. Comparison between cyclogenesis density calculated from tracking or large scale combined variables (as a modified Gray parameter) brings some confidence in the use of the latter to investigate low resolution simulations. Mean hurricane dynamical characteristics are weakly changed by the warming but precipitation core and latent heat flux are enhanced in all scenarios. © Springer-Verlag 2006.",,"climate variation; computer simulation; global warming; heat flux; hurricane; sea surface temperature; vortex",,,,,,"Ayrault, F., Environnement, structure et évolution des dépressions mt́éorologiques: Réalité climatologique et modèles types (1998), p. 328. , Ph.D. thesis. Universite' Paul Sabatier Toulouse, France, [Available from Université Paul Sabatier, 118 Route de Narbonne, 31062, Toulouse, France]Ayrault, F., Joly, A., Une nouvelle typologie des dépresssions météorologiques: Classification des phases de maturation (2000) Compte-Rendus à L'Académie Des Sciences, Sciences De La Terre Et Des Planètes, 330, pp. 167-172; Bengtsson, L., Bottger, H., Kanamitsu, M., Simulation of hurricane-type vortices in a general circulation model (1982) Tellus, 34, pp. 440-457; Bengtsson, L., Botzet, M., Esch, M., Hurricane-type vortices in a general circulation model (1995) Tellus, 47 A, pp. 175-196; Bougeault, P., A simple parameterization of the large-scale effects of cumulus convection (1985) Mon Weather Rev, 113, pp. 2108-2121; Broccoli, A., Manabe, S., Can existing climate models be used to study anthropogenic changes in tropical cyclone climate? (1990) Geophys Res Lett, 17, pp. 1917-1920; Camargo, S., Zebiak, S., Improving the detection and tracking of tropical cyclones in atmospheric general circulation models (2002) Weather Forcast, 17, pp. 1152-1162; Courtier, P., Geleyn, J.F., A global numerical weather prediction model with variable resolution: Application to a shallow water equation (1988) Quart J R Meteor Soc, 114, pp. 1321-1346; Courtier, P., Freydier, C., Geleyn, J.F., Rabier, F., Rochas, M., The ARPEGE project at METEO-FRANCE (1991) ECMWF Seminar Proceedings, 2, pp. 193-221. , reading, 9-13 Sept 1991; Déqué, M., (1999), Documentation ARPEGE-CLIMAT. Tech report Centre National de Recherches Météorologiques, Météo-France, Toulouse, FranceDéqué, M., Piéde